ce:section.ce:para:
The size distribution and morphology the of as-synthesized CQDs were investigated with TEM. For this purpose, the aqueous solution of CQDs was coated on a copper grid and vaporized at room temperature. TEM image (Fig. 1
                        ) suggests that the CQDs are near spherical nanocrystals with narrow size distribution about 2 nm. This is in agreement with the result of approximately 2.9 nm hydrodynamic diameter from dynamic light scattering (Fig. 2
                        ) because the dry-state diameter is slightly smaller than the hydrodynamic diameter. DLS was carried out using 633 nm laser source at of 90° scattering angle. In this technique, the appearing and disappearing rate of the scattering patterns were related to particle diffusion and convert to size and size distribution using the Stokes Einstein equation.

The typical XRD patterns of the CQDs (Fig. 3
                        ) was shown a peak centered at 20° [32]. The functional groups were characterized by FTIR. The FT-IR spectra of modified CQDs display characteristic spectra compared to free FA molecules and CQDs (Fig. 4
                        ) that have shown generally retained the molecular structure of folic acid. Broad absorption centered at 3424 cm−1 and the sharp peak at 1638 cm−1 can be due to the stretching vibration of N–H, O–H and the stretching vibration of amide and CO groups respectively. The absorption peaks at 2889-2952 cm−1 are assigned to aliphatic groups of folic acid that were shown the successful modification of quantum dots with folic acid.

The optical properties of the FA-CQDs were studied using the fluorescence emission and the UV–vis absorption spectra. Also the quantum yield of the synthesized dots was determined. The aqueous dispersion of CQDs has continua below 400 nm with a peak at 340 nm (Fig. 5
                        ). These can be due to π-π* and n-π* transition of CC and CO groups respectively. The photoluminescence spectra of the brown solution of synthesized nanocrystals were recorded in the range of 370−600 nm with 360 nm excitation wavelength and 450 nm emission maximum was obtained (Fig. 6
                        ). When CDs excited from 320 to 370, the corresponding PL emission peak does not display impressive shifts. This situation is eventuating of the size distribution and surface states of the carbon quantum dots. The quantum yield of the CQDs and FA-CQDs was 6.5 % and 50 % respectively, indicating that present of folic acid on the surface can impressively improve the luminescence efficiency of the C-dots.
